It seems to me that any warning which can be suppressed by using an @SuppressWarnings annotation should then be ignored if that warning is changed in the compiler options to be an error.

For example, take the following class:
public class ErrorTest {
    private String getTest() {
        return "test";
    }
}

If "Unused local or private member" is set to "Warning" in the compiler options, this will cause a warning.

If the class is annotated with @SuppressWarnings("unused"), then the warning will vanish. However, if "Unused local or private member" is then changed to "error", the suppression ceases to have any effect.

While I can see the argument that you can't suppress JLS errors, so why should you be able to suppress things you have elevated to that level, it seems more _useful_ to me to be able to suppress these also. When trying to clean up a codebase to get rid of warnings, it's good to be able to change them to errors as you go in order to enforce discipline; in the rare case that a warning must be suppressed, it would be extremely useful to still escalate the priority of the warning to error.

Errors are not suppressable per definition. If you made a warning into an error, then it is far more severe; and thus cannot be suppressed any longer. At least not by a @SuppressWarnings annotation, which only affects warnings, not errors.
@SuppressOptionalError... is not planned in the short term future. You should rather question the fact you raised certain warnings into errors. If you want to be able to ignore them, then you did not mean these to be errors.
